<h3>
    <strong>1. Willamette River (Portland to Oregon City)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        A rare urban river offering <strong>spring Chinook</strong> runs in April–May, and <strong>fall Coho</strong> in September–October.
    </li>
    <li>
        Bank anglers often fish at <strong>Meldrum Bar</strong>, <strong>Clackamette Park</strong>, and <strong>Sellwood Riverfront Park</strong>, while boat anglers troll herring or spinners in deeper river sections.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>2. Clackamas River</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Just 20–30 minutes southeast of Portland. Excellent for both <strong>spring Chinook</strong> and <strong>fall Coho</strong>, with strong <strong>steelhead</strong>runs too.
    </li>
    <li>
        Fishing access at <strong>Carver Park</strong>, <strong>Riverside Park</strong>, <strong>High Rocks</strong>, and <strong>Milo McIver State Park</strong>. Drift fishing with roe or jigs is highly effective.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>3. Sandy River</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Around 20 minutes east of Portland, offers consistent spring and fall Chinook, along with <strong>Coho</strong> and <strong>steelhead</strong>.
    </li>
    <li>
        Prime access points include <strong>Dodge Park</strong>, <strong>Lewis &amp; Clark State Park</strong>, <strong>Oxbow Regional Park</strong>, and near the hatchery at Cedar Creek.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>4. Multnomah Channel (Sauvie Island area)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        A quieter tributary of the Willamette River, productive for <strong>spring Chinook</strong> and fall runs.
    </li>
    <li>
        Popular banks include <strong>Scappoose Bay</strong> and areas near the Gilbert River. Techniques like back-bouncing bait or trolling near structure are effective.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>5. Tillamook Bay &amp; Nehalem River (Coastal Options)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        About 1.5 hours from Portland, offering some of the best trophy <strong>fall Chinook and Coho</strong> fishing within reach.
    </li>
    <li>
        Use plug-cut herring or trolling techniques in tidal zones and river mouths.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>6. Wilson &amp; Trask Rivers (Tillamook Coast)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Scenic rivers offering <strong>fall Chinook</strong> and <strong>winter steelhead</strong> in a more remote setting (~1.5 hours away).
    </li>
</ul>
