</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Spring Chinook</strong> peak in the Willamette and Clackamas in April–May.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Fall Coho</strong> primarily run Clackamas and Sandy Rivers in September–October.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Techniques &amp; Gear Recommendations
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Trolling</strong>: Use flashers, herring, or Anchovies in Columbia, Willamette, and Multnomah Channel.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Drift Fishing</strong>: Especially productive on Clackamas and Sandy Rivers using roe clusters or jigs.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Bank Fishing</strong>: Effective at Clackamette, Meldrum Bar, and Sandy “Dodge Park”, especially for hatchery Chinook and Coho.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Rules &amp; Regulations
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>License &amp; Combined Angling Tag</strong> are required for Chinook, Coho, steelhead, and other inland species.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Columbia River Endorsement</strong> is also required when fishing in Columbia tributaries or estuary zones.
    </li>
    <li>
        Be mindful of <strong>size limits, daily bag limits</strong>, and closures—especially for wild salmon stocks.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Local Tips &amp; Observations
</h2>
<blockquote>
    <p>
        “The springer run is happening on the Willamette … You can fish the Clackamas from Riverside Park, Carver Park, Barton Park… The Sandy at Lewis &amp; Clark, Dabney, Oxbow, Dodge Park…”
    </p>
    <p>
        “Sandy is indeed a good spot … hatchery coho season for Clackamas and Sandy runs Sept‑Oct.”
    </p>
</blockquote>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Sandy and Clackamas Rivers</strong> remain top public bank fisheries—especially during high coho runs.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Multnomah Channel</strong> often has better bite and less crowding than the main river.
    </li>
    <li>
        For those with boats, <strong>Columbia River fishing</strong> at Kelly Point and Sauvie Island is excellent in summer and fall.
    </li>
</ul>

